Eu0.0062Tb0.0087Gd0.9851L triple-emitting white MOF material was synthesized with a tetracarboxylic acid organic ligand H4L and lanthanide ions (Eu3+, Tb3+, Gd3+). It is worth noting that since the lowest excited state of Gd3+ is higher than the lowest excited state of the ligand, the energy transfer cannot be from the ligand to Gd3+. The main role of Gd3+ in this composite is to act as a matrix for the synthesis of MOF and to dilute the other two lanthanide ions. When the excitation wavelength is in the range of 350 ∼ 390 nm, red light from Eu3+, green light from Tb3+, and blue light from the ligand can be gained simultaneously. White light emission can be generated under excitation at 380 ∼ 390 nm (Fig. 1
                           ).[48] Similarly, Sun et al. also synthesized a three-emission white fluorescent material Eu0.059Tb0.051Gd0.89-DPON (H3DPON = 5-(3,4-dicarboxylphenoxy) nicotic acid) by encapsulating Eu3+, Tb3+and Gd3+ ions.[49] Another MOF with white luminescence was also successfully constructed using Eu(NO3)3·6H2O, Tb(NO3)3·6H2O, Gd(NO3)3·6H2O (molar ratio 0.06:0.04:0.9) and ligand H3DPNC as raw materials.[50] Using 5-boronoisophthalic as ligand, boric acid can recognize diol and Lewis base, which can improve the ability of MOF multi-target detection. When Eu3+ and Tb3+ were used as metal sources to construct white hair light composites, the blue luminescence from the ligands disappeared. When Dy-MOF is used as the substrate, the emission peak of Dy3+ changes to a wide emission peak covering the blue emission peak of the ligand. Finally, when the ratio of Eu3+, Tb3+ and Dy3+ was adjusted to 0.3:0.3:0.3/0.4, the MOF composite with white light emission was successfully constructed, and a single probe was used to detect multi-target analytes (Fig. 2
                           ).[51] The research group further reported that a MOF gel with three emission colors was successfully constructed by combining 5-boronisophthalic acid (5-bop) and Tb3+, Eu3+ and Dy3+.[52].

Nitroaromatic compounds are the primary components of most explosives, rapid and accurate recognition of such compounds in complex environments is essential for the prevention of violent crime and terrorist attacks in public places. On the other hand, the detection of NACs in soil, air, and water environments are also significant for human health due to the biological toxicity of the compounds themselves.[83–85] Finding low-cost, high-sensitivity detection methods to meet current society needs has become a pressing issue, and ratiometric sensors based on MOFs with multiple emission centers stand out. Ni et al.'s research group prepared a variety of three-dimensional ratio sensors, including D, W2, Z3, V4. The MOF composite D ((0.017 wt％[Pt]++0.046 wt％[Ru]2+)@1) with white light emission was studied. Nitrobenzene, 4-nitrotoluene, 1,3-dinitrobenzene, 1-nitronaphthalene, 2-nitrophenol, 4-nitrophenol and dinitrophenol were selected for detection. The result showed that the quenching effect of DNBP on D was the most obvious. The first three analytes could not be distinguished in the two-dimensional maps of IL/I[Pt]
                           + and IL/I[Ru]
                           2+, but 1-NP, 2-NPHEN, 4-NPHEN and DNBP could be clearly separated in the high NAC concentration stage. After adding the titration amount as the third dimension, 2-NPHEN and 4-NPHEN can be distinguished, which cannot be achieved in the 2D diagram. The quenching of D by NAC can be seen from the two units of ligand and encapsulated luminescent module. The quenching of ligand is caused by electron transfer and fluorescence resonance energy transfer between ligand and NAC, hydrogen bond and electrostatic interaction between them. On the one hand, the quenching of ELM is directly caused by NAC, on the other hand, it is caused by the decrease of energy transfer to ELM after the ligand is quenched. Different from other reports, D realizes the difference of liquid nitroaromatics. This strategy expands the actual detection range of nitroaromatics (Fig. 12
                           ).[56] The previously mentioned W2 can also be used for sensing identification of nitroaromatic explosives. A special combination of two emission ratios and time variations achieves the first 3D identifier for the target nitroaromatic vapor (Fig. 13
                           ).[57] The three-dimensional fingerprint of NAC vapor was established by using IMOF/IPt, IMOF/IRu and time. Six NACs can be clearly distinguished in 20 min. In similar AC vapor 3D fingerprints, EA, NH3 and 1,3-PA have their own unique allocation trajectories. In addition, the Z3 sensor can distinguish between N-PRNH2 and NBUNH2 within 23 min, and can distinguish between DMA and DPA after 15 min. A practical test strip was prepared with Z3, and the color changes of the above vapors can be clearly observed by the naked eye. Z3 shows more excellent performance than the previously reported three-color sensor (Fig. 14
                           ).[58] The group further studied the encapsulation of [Ru(by3)]2+ and [ACF]+ to modify the anionic MOF {(Me2NH2)3Cd0.5 [Cd3L]·6DMF·9H2O(1)}, and constructed a 3D ratio sensor with three main emission (450 nm, 495 nm, 600 nm). Introducing time as the third dimension, the constructed 3-DRS can distinguish 7 NAC vapors, 4 groups of regional isomers and 3 groups of O-/M-/P-monosubstituted NBS.[86].

Due to the massive use and continuous release of antibiotics, the level of environmental pollution is increasing year by year, and antibiotic residues have become one of the most serious threats to global public health, so it is important to develop efficient, rapid, and simple antibiotic detection methods.[87] Dy-TCPB with three emission centers was prepared by LnCl3-6H2O and H3TCPB = 1,3,5-tris(1-(2-carboxyphenyl)-1H-pyrazole-3-yl) benzene. The two ratios of the ligand to the emission intensity of Dy3+（I385/I481、I385/I573）are X-axis and Y-axis. The double-readout 2D decoding map can effectively distinguish multiple antibiotics. Higher detection sensitivity for furacilin (NFZ) and furazolidone (FZD) with relevant detection limits of 0.0476 µM and 0.0482 µM. After adding concentration, a new 3D code recognition scheme is obtained, which can detect antibiotics and reads their concentrations (Fig. 15
                           ). The UV absorption spectra show that the absorption bands of NFZ and FZD overlap with the absorption bands of tcpb3, and NFZ and FZD absorb the excitation energy to reduce the energy transfer of TCPB3--Dy3+. At the same time, the LUMO energy levels of H3TCPB, NFZ and FZD are analyzed. The obvious gap difference between the LUMO energy level of H3TCPB and the LUMO energy level of NFZ and FZD indicates that the process of Dy-TCPB quenching induced by NFZ and FZD is the result of energy competition absorption and Pet interaction (Fig. 16
                           ).[88].
